# 

<span key="0acc1fdb68d945f2a483ba62e58733ab"><span offset-key="0acc1fdb68d945f2a483ba62e58733ab:0">JavaScript Null vs Undefined</span></span>

> <span key="0378ec353b064bf883e739353e9cdec0"><span offset-key="0378ec353b064bf883e739353e9cdec0:0">Understanding the difference between null and undefined</span></span>

<span key="355709df5488479383275d68eb552c69"><span offset-key="355709df5488479383275d68eb552c69:0">Null and Undefined are both data types in JavaScript.</span></span>

<span key="b51c994b59a84773b5d8b1510540d467">**Undefined**<span offset-key="b51c994b59a84773b5d8b1510540d467:1"> is a variable that has been declared but not assigned a value.</span></span>

<span key="ac661bfe675e4c01869f29fa19d8b995">**Null**<span offset-key="ac661bfe675e4c01869f29fa19d8b995:1"> as an assignment value. So you can assign the value </span>`null`<span offset-key="ac661bfe675e4c01869f29fa19d8b995:3"> to any variable which basically means it’s blank.</span></span>

<span key="e63de7f0822f430aa40ca301ff63428a"><span offset-key="e63de7f0822f430aa40ca301ff63428a:0">So by not declaring a value to a variable, JavaScript automatically assigns the value to </span>`undefined`<span offset-key="e63de7f0822f430aa40ca301ff63428a:2">. However, when you assign </span>`null`<span offset-key="e63de7f0822f430aa40ca301ff63428a:4"> to a variable, you are declaring that this value is </span>*explicitly empty*<span offset-key="e63de7f0822f430aa40ca301ff63428a:6">.</span></span>

<span key="878d06dd779c43b69b28f36b8759d680"><span offset-key="878d06dd779c43b69b28f36b8759d680:0">Null and Undefined</span></span>

<span key="38c9bf1aa9b14176875a2bfaaf745607"><span offset-key="38c9bf1aa9b14176875a2bfaaf745607:0">JavaScript will never automatically assign the value to </span>`null`<span offset-key="38c9bf1aa9b14176875a2bfaaf745607:2">. That must be done by you in your code.</span></span>

<span key="92c05346c5a44566ae29359284f43c6a"><span offset-key="92c05346c5a44566ae29359284f43c6a:0">Let’s get some more info on these.</span></span>

<span key="c6e55577fa844f4696eca3fd1a969c9d"><span offset-key="c6e55577fa844f4696eca3fd1a969c9d:0">Typeof null and undefined</span></span>

<span key="3d02f1aa8cd74302ab2b25cd8b16d829"><span offset-key="3d02f1aa8cd74302ab2b25cd8b16d829:0">We see here that the type of </span>`null`<span offset-key="3d02f1aa8cd74302ab2b25cd8b16d829:2"> is an </span>**object**<span offset-key="3d02f1aa8cd74302ab2b25cd8b16d829:4"> but the type of </span>`undefined`<span offset-key="3d02f1aa8cd74302ab2b25cd8b16d829:6"> is </span>**undefined**<span offset-key="3d02f1aa8cd74302ab2b25cd8b16d829:8">.</span></span>

<span key="becf5144417d45528f317762dc78d046"><span offset-key="becf5144417d45528f317762dc78d046:0">Since these are different data types, if we compare them with strict equality </span>`===`<span offset-key="becf5144417d45528f317762dc78d046:2">, we get </span>`false`<span offset-key="becf5144417d45528f317762dc78d046:4">.</span></span>

<span key="66858f316167477fb7fe31b35016f3e7"><span offset-key="66858f316167477fb7fe31b35016f3e7:0">Comparison between null and undefined</span></span>

<span key="6327832517584922890a917ede0357d4"><span offset-key="6327832517584922890a917ede0357d4:0">But if we compare them with abstract equality </span>`==`<span offset-key="6327832517584922890a917ede0357d4:2">, we get </span>`true`<span offset-key="6327832517584922890a917ede0357d4:4">.</span></span>

<span key="c63a40b58c914ef8b8f74dd04c56a8b9"><span offset-key="c63a40b58c914ef8b8f74dd04c56a8b9:0">So JavaScript does consider these to be relatively equal since they both represent an empty value.</span></span>

<span key="cb41bed113dd482cbf02dcec8ceba69f"><span offset-key="cb41bed113dd482cbf02dcec8ceba69f:0">So if you need to check if a value is either </span>`null`<span offset-key="cb41bed113dd482cbf02dcec8ceba69f:2"> or </span>`undefined`<span offset-key="cb41bed113dd482cbf02dcec8ceba69f:4">, you can check for abstract equality and compare it to either null or undefined. Both will return the same result.</span></span>
